[normal]s emerged in terms of those whom
[normal] Monitor believe are receiving historic underfunding, or who are significantly below what the Government have said is their target, for example, and the existence of trusts that are failing financially? Is there a pattern there?
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: Of course
[normal] the funding allocation goes to commissioners, not to the trusts.
[normal]Andrew George:[bold] 
[normal]Quite, yes.
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: 
[normal]But then, of course, it finds its way to the trusts. In so far as what the trusts are paid is dependent on payment by results, or at least payment by activity, then you might say, to a certain extent, it does not matter how the commissioners are funded. If they 
[normal]are 
[normal]doing 
[normal]the activity, they get paid for it. In truth, of course, there 
[normal]is 
[normal]a big chunk of what they do that gets paid for not through payment by results but through block contracts or similar arrangements. What we can say is that
[normal],
[normal] often
[normal],
[normal] where we have a struggling trust
[normal],
[normal] we also have a struggling health economy. As to whether they are struggling as a health economy because they are underfunded
[normal],
[normal] it is a bit difficult for us to say, but you often see a struggling trust and an economy struggling
[normal],
[normal] and commissioners and maybe other trusts in the area struggling as well.
[normal]Q12 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrew George:[bold] 
[normal]The NHS 
[normal]Confederation
[normal] say
[normal]s
[normal] that your role should be expanded or you should take on the
[normal] role of supporting financially 
[normal]challenged trusts. We know that you are the sector regulator, or at least have been. To what extent do you believe that you have a pastoral role, as it were, in supporting and assisting financ
[normal]ially 
[normal]challenged trusts?  
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: 
[normal]If a trust gets into difficulty
[normal],
[normal] it is most certainly our job
[normal]—
[normal]and this is what
[normal] Stephen spends his days doing—
[normal]whether it is because of the quality of the care they are providing or their financial position
