[normal],
[normal] that may need money. We do not hold that money. We have to go to the Depa
[normal]rtment of Health,
[normal] sometimes in support of or alongside a trust, depending on the specific circumstances, and make a case for funding. We will only do that if we are satisfied that they have a credible plan to turn themselves around and a credible leadership to implement that plan. Sometimes
[normal],
[normal] we will find a situation where the problems at the trust are quite structural in nature, things like being very small or having multiple sites and all these sorts of factors.
[normal]Stephen Hay[bold]: 
[normal]Or PFI.
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: 
[normal]A big PFI is another good example. Under those circumstances
[normal],
[normal] we may have to seek more significant action to fix the problem, including restructuring the services. That is something that we are going to see more of in the coming years.
[normal]Q13 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrew [bold]George
[normal]:[bold] 
[normal]To what extent does that role harmonise with that o
[normal]f the Trust Development Agency—
[normal]the TDA?
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: 
[normal]Yes, completely. We work very closely with the TDA for two reasons. One, we are essentially both doing the same thing. They have a much more direct hands
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]on relationship with their trusts
[normal],
[normal] but, frankly, once our trusts are in serious difficulty
[normal],
[normal] we have a pretty hands
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]on relationship with them as well. What we are trying to do with them is the same thing
[normal],
[normal] and, furthermore, because there is this phenomenon of 
[normal]“
[normal]struggling trusts often m
[normal]ean struggling health economies”,
[normal] you often find neighbouring trusts in difficulty and you cannot fix one without fixing another. A very good illustration of this is 
[normal]that 
[normal]we have a struggling trust in 
[normal]Milton Keynes
[normal]. They had some quality problems
[normal]; they
[normal] fixed the quality problems
[normal],
[normal] but then they became financial problems. It is now pretty clear that the financial problems can be fixed only with some rather more fundamental restructuring
[normal] of services. The TDA has a not-far-
[normal]away trust at Bedford
[normal],
[normal] which has both quality and financial problems. Rather than try and fix them separately we have, along with NHS England, commissioned some work to look across the whole health economy led by the commissioners
[normal], because t
[normal]hat is where 
[normal]we
[normal] have to start, to try and work out what the pattern of services needs to be in that whole health economy
[normal],
[normal] and then, as a result of that, work out what we are going to do with Milton Keynes and what the TDA is going to do with Bedford. 
[normal]Q14 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Andrew George:[bold] 
[normal]Are there any lessons to be learned from the work that you have done so far in terms of
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]“Is there a pattern of financially
[normal] failing and quality of patient outcome failing trusts?
[normal]”
[normal] Do the two go hand in hand
[normal]? W
[normal]here there a
[normal]re financially troubled trusts, i
[normal]s the pattern, in other words, the cause of that financial difficulty? Are there common themes which run through th
[normal]e trusts that you have found that
[normal] are in difficulty?
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: 
[normal]Yes. We have done some work on them and Stephen might like to talk about that.
[normal]Stephen Hay[bold]: 
[normal]There is no doubt that where there are quality failings they almost inevitably then lead into financial failings because fixing the quality adds to the cost base. You can see at places like Mid Staffordshire, Milton Keynes and 
[normal]Morecambe
[normal] 
[normal]Bay
[normal] that substantial increases in the cost base then lead to financial difficulties. Actual financial failings, as David has said, could be a wide range of things from bad management, structural problems
[normal] and
[normal] big unaffordable PFI schemes to problems in the local health economy with the commissioners unable to afford the services that are being provided. 
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: T
[normal]here are two important lessons that certainly I have learned over my time at Monitor. The first was to look at a very early stage
[normal],
[normal] where you have a financially troubled trust
[normal],
[normal] as to whether or not there are structu
[normal]ral issues. To a certain extent, in the past,
[normal] we used to focus on the leadership of the trust, the board, the management of the trust
[normal],
[normal] and say, 
[normal]“I
[normal]f they are failing, 
[normal]often almost invariably there a
[normal]re weaknesses in the management
[normal],” and we would try and fix that. But increasingly—
[normal]and I think this is partly a reflection of the margin for things being less than perfect shrink
[normal]ing—
[normal]we are seeing that even when you fix the management, if there are underlying structural problems, you still have not fixed the financial problem. Then that extends how long it takes to fix it. So one of the lessons is, at a very early stage, to try and understand if there are structural problems
[normal],
[normal] so that we can get 
[normal]going on those straight away. 
[normal]The second lesson I have learned
[normal]—
[normal]and this is a particularly recent one in a way
[normal]—
[normal]is that we have a failu
[normal]re regime which is institutionally based: it is
[normal] abou
[normal]t individual trusts. W
[normal]e are applying it for the first time at Mid Staffordshire
[normal],
[normal] and the TDA ap
[normal]plied it for the first time in 
[normal]S
[normal]outh London
[normal]. 
[normal]Particularly looking at Mid Staffordshire, what is absolutely clear is that we have a health economy that is 
[normal]failing
[normal] and the worst consequence of that is in Mid Staffordshire, but it is most certainly not confined to Mid Staffordshire. 
[normal]W
[normal]hat we really need is a failure regime for health economies. We can construct that and that is effectively what we are trying do with Milton Keynes and Bedford now
[normal],
[normal] to say they are not in failure but they are struggling and we need to look at the whole health economy, not just individual institutions.
