[normal]Q41 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Dr Wollaston:[bold] 
[normal]Moving on to another issue, Sir David Nicholson told us that in his view we are getting 
[normal]“
[normal]bogged down in a morass of competition law, which is causing significant cost in the system.
[normal]”
[normal] He believes that legislative change may be required. Dr Bennett, what 
[normal]is 
[normal]your view on that and, with the Care Bill coming up
[normal], perhaps you could elaborate 
[normal]wh
[normal]at change you would like to see.
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: 
[normal]This is, I think, quite a complex issue. There are
[normal] two ways in which competition issues—
[normal]or things that a
[normal]re perceived to be competition issues—
[normal]are concerning people. One is around mergers and the other is around what commissioners do. 
[normal]I
[normal]f I could take the commissioner issues first, particularly the application of the so
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]called section 75 regulations
[normal]—
[normal]the procurement, patient choice and competition regulation
[normal]—
[normal]I think, unfortunately, there is an awful lot of misunderstanding and misinformation out there as to what those regulations do and do not require. They are not even fundamentally about competition. They are about doing commissioning well
[normal],
[normal] and in fact they say that competition is only one of the tools available to a commissioner to secure better services for their patients. They even explicitly talk about other things like, in particul
[normal]ar, better integration of care.
[normal]These rules, apart from that bit about better integration, are essentially the same as the rules that have been in existence for quite some time. They used to be the 
[normal]“
[normal]Principles and rules 
[normal]for co-operation and competition”.
[normal] They are hardly changed and the regulations are pretty well the same as the old rules. The biggest change is that we have different peo
[normal]ple doing the commissioning now, 
[normal]for a whole variety of reasons, and I think
[normal]—
[normal]not least, unfortunately, because it has become an 
[normal]incredibly controversial issue—
[normal]those commissioners are very concerned about what this means for them. Fundamentally, if they are doing good commissioning that is improving the quality of care for their patients
[normal],
[normal] they should not have any problems
[normal],
[normal] but this is clearly not the perception. So
[normal],
[normal] on 
[normal]this front, above all
[normal] we have to find ways of talking to these commissioners
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]helping
[normal] them 
[normal]to 
[normal]understand what the rules really mean
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]here is a whole variety of things 
[normal]that 
[normal]we need 
[normal]to do there
[normal] and I have been in 
[normal]conversation with David Nic
[normal]holson about how we can do this. Working
[normal] jointly with NHS England 
[normal]on this 
[normal]will be very helpful because they have significant influence on commissioners and how 
[normal]they
[normal] think about these things. I am hoping that
[normal],
[normal] if we can explain to commissioners what it is that the rules do and do not allow them to do
[normal],
[normal] we can deal with that, but I recognise that it is a huge challenge to explain it to people and there is a whole variety 
[normal]of things that we need to do. 
[normal]On mergers, of course, what happened was that from April
[normal]—
[normal]and in fact before April
[normal]—
[normal]the OFT took over responsibility for looking at mergers involving foundation trusts
[normal],
[normal] and
[normal],
[normal] again
[normal],
[normal] here I think that there 
[normal]is a huge amount
[normal] of concern about the implication of the way those rules are being applied. People will cite Poole and 
[normal]Bournemouth
[normal] as an example of where the rules got in the way of doing what some people at least think was the right thing to do. There 
[normal]is
[normal] again a variety of issues, some of which 
[normal]are
[normal] just about trying to help people understand what they can and cannot do, and there is a lot we can do on that front. One of the things with a merger is that it is extremely important to start with a good understanding of why it is that a merger is the right thing to do. I should say
[normal] that
[normal], even where mergers have been allowed, the track record is not great. 
[normal]B
[normal]eing absolutely clear that
[normal],
[normal] whatever the problem that a 
[normal]trust
[normal] or a pair of trusts face
[normal]s
[normal], merger is the right answer is the starting point
[normal],
[normal] and I think we can help
[normal]—
[normal]it is a bit more about shortening the length of that arm
[normal]—
[normal]to try and make sure that they have that right. 
[normal]The next bit is about understanding what the competition issues 
[normal]are 
[normal]that they need to worry about. 
[normal]F
[normal]or whatever reason, people are hearing all sorts of strange messages about concerns which we do not, frankly, understand. So we need to do more to explain to people what are the likely competition issues and what sort of advice they need
[normal],
[normal] if they do need advice
[normal],
[normal] to deal with those issues. In fact
[normal],
[normal] we are going to go a step further, which is to do for ourselves, in parallel with the trusts thinking about whether or not they want to proceed with the merger, some of the work that the OFT would do so that we can help the trusts to understand, 
[normal]or 
[normal]the parties to understand, whether or not they are likely to have any issues and help them think through what they would do about it. If all of that is done well, that should deal with a lot of the problems we have. 
[normal]T
[normal]here is another issue and I am not sure how to deal with 
[normal]it
[normal]. This is about how you think about whether competition issues should be an obstacle to allowing a merger to proceed. The way the competition authorities think about this is that they first of all ask themselves
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]“
[normal]Is there a significant lessening of competition?
[normal]”
[normal] If the answer is yes, they then say, 
[normal]“
[normal]Is this likely to be outweighed by the patient benefits that would accrue from allowing the merger to proceed anyway?
[normal]”
[normal] Then they try and work out exactly, or get the parties to tell them exactly, what those patient benefits would be. The problem is that there is a presumption that if there is a significant lessening of competition that is bad
[normal],
[normal] and therefore you have to look at the concrete benefits of the merger and see whether they outweigh them. But the connection between there being a significant lessening of competition and that driving improvement in the quality or efficiency of care is a fairly tenuous connection. It is difficult. We can look at studies that tell us that competition does have some
[normal] impact on the quality of care—and t
[normal]here are some studie
[normal]s done in England to show that—
[normal]but to translate that into, 
[normal]“
[normal]How fast and how effectively would that competition improve the quality of care?
[normal]” 
[normal]is very difficult. 
