[normal]Q105 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Valerie [bold]Vaz[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]That leads me lastly on to the next area. The Select Committee and Robert Francis in his seminal work on Mid Staffordshire both said that 
[normal]there should not be two of you—CQC and Monitor—
[normal]but you think there should be. Could you explain why? 
[normal]Dr Bennett[bold]: 
[normal]First, I should say that that is a decision, ultimately, for the Government. However, I do share the Government
[normal]’
[normal]s view that merging the two organisations would not be the right thing to do. That is for two fundamental reasons. First of all, if you were starting from scratch and there was no CQC and no Monitor and you were asking, 
[normal]“
[normal]How do you regulate this sector?
[normal]”
[normal] there is an argument, I absolutely accept, for saying you will draw a dividing line between the two organisations in a different place to where it is today and maybe even just have one organisation. You could make that argument
[normal];
[normal] I would not. I would say that, while that would provide some benefits, there is a huge merit in separating the body that says whether or not care is good enough from the body whose job it is to sort it out. Similarly, I think there is huge merit in separating the body that looks at the quality of care from the body that has to worry about whether the finances of a trust are in good order. This is as I said before: whenever we have a trust in difficulty, the first thing that we care about is getting the quality fixed and then we will sort the finances out. So
[normal],
[normal] even with a blank sheet of paper, I personally would keep them separate. However, we do not have a blank sheet of paper. We have two organisations, both of which have been going through
[normal]—
[normal]or, in the case of the CQC, still are going through
[normal]—
[normal]a lot of change
[normal],
[normal] and I think the last thing you would need is to add to that the complexity and challenges of putting the two together. Indeed, you could argue that some of the challeng
[normal]es that the CQC has
[normal] faced have been a consequence of the fact that it was three separate organisations put together and 
[normal]that 
[normal]it is a challenging thing to do. I would not do it for that reason. 
